1 (d) "Reasonable apprehension of bodily injury" means a belief that bodily injury is imminent and
2 the same belief would be held by a reasonable person under similar circumstances, even if bodily injury
3 ultimately does not occur.
4 (3) (a) (i) An offender convicted of partner or family member assault shall be fined an amount not
5 less than $100 or more than $1,000 and be imprisoned in the county jail for a term not to exceed 1 year or not
6 less than 24 hours for a first offense.
7 (ii) An offender convicted of a second offense under this section shall be fined not less than $300
8 or more than $1,000 and be imprisoned in the county jail not less than 72 hours or more than 1 year.
9 (iii) Upon a first or second conviction, the offender may be ordered into misdemeanor probation as
10 provided in 46-23-1005.
11 (iv) On a third or subsequent conviction for partner or family member assault, the offender shall be
12 fined not less than $500 and not more than $50,000 and be imprisoned for a term not less than 30 days and not
13 more than 5 years. If the term of imprisonment does not exceed 1 year, the person shall be imprisoned in the
14 county jail. If the term of imprisonment exceeds 1 year, the person shall be imprisoned in the state prison.
15 (v) If the offense was committed within the vision or hearing of a minor, the judge shall consider
16 the minor's presence as a factor at the time of sentencing.
17 (b) For the purpose of determining the number of convictions under this section, a conviction
18 means:
19 (i) a conviction, as defined in 45-2-101, under this section;
20 (ii) a conviction for domestic abuse under this section;
21 (iii) a conviction for a violation of a statute similar to this section in another state;
22 (iv) if the offender was a partner or family member of the victim, a conviction for aggravated assault
23 under 45-5-202 or assault with a weapon under 45-5-213;
24 (v) a conviction for strangulation of a partner or family member under 45-5-215;
25 (vi) a conviction in another state for an offense related to domestic violence between partners or
26 family members, as those terms are defined in this section, regardless of what the offense is named or whether
27 it is misdemeanor or felony, if the offense involves conduct similar to conduct that is prohibited under 45-5-202,
28 45-5-213, or this section; or
